76561197988509871,Not Recommended,238430,8349957,"Posted: 27 December, 2013",all,poomanchu,"My first impressions aren't great.  I've found the movement jerky, the leaning-while-strafing annoying, the hit-recognition terrible, and the ""find-the-mission-item-to-proceed"" and general inventory implementation a bit frustrating.It seems like the movement was coded to represent someone constantly out-of-breath, always struggling to take the next step.  It's almost like the character is shuffling like a zombie from the get-go.  Running just makes the effect even more pronounced.  Also, when you strafe left or right, the game adds a leaning effect to your movement.  Maybe it's an attempt to progress the state of game movement, but instead, it just feels awkward.  I would guess that most users expect left/right to act the same as forward/backward as far as camera-bob is concerned.  In this case, the leaning seems to add a touch of lag to left/right movement.  Why couldn't they just add additional buttons to provide the ability lean left/right rather than mix it with the default strafing buttons?In the most recent patch, it's stated that hit-box computations were tweaked, but I found myself missing at point-blank range all of the time.  Multiple times, I found myself emptying an entire clip into a zombies face with zero effect, only to take damage once the clip was empty.My complaint with the mission item revolves around the first 'find-the-key' objective.  The devs stated that they simplified the act of finding the key, but I still wasted a half-hour of no zombie-killing doing laps trying to find the elusive key.  After 6 laps around the open parts of the level, I was bored, totally removed from the action, assuming that the item just didn't exist.  I finally looked it up in the Steam community threads to get a slight hint about it being at eye-level hanging from some sort of rack.  When a game totally removes you from the action to find an item, I would consider it poor quest implementation.My last complaint is about inventory.  Reading through the community discussions, my complaint certainly isn't unique.  I mean, really?!?!  You have to discard one of your four weapons to hold a single key?!?!  Does a key really weigh as much as a shotgun or assault rifle?  In no reasonable way should I have to throw a gun on the floor to carry a single key across a level.  Additionally, it's recommended to keep the key to try on different doors, so I feel forced to continually waste 1 of the 4 item slots on said single key *just in case* there's a second door somewhere that could possible be unlocked by it.Maybe I'll try the game when it's no longer in 'Early Access' and provide a different view of the game.  Until then, I cannot recommend this game to the causual gamer thinking that this game is in an entertaining, playable form."
