76561197975359487,Recommended,238430,11916484,"Posted: 29 August, 2014",all,Savage,"So if it wasn't due to the F2P weekend, myself and my mates probably would have never heard of this, and put it down to a 'risky purchase' title, due to its price when it's not on sale. Thankfully, after getting into this game with a couple of mates, I have to say this has been the best co-op experience I've had for quite sometime.Now, this is based on my experience with two other mates, on TS. Not random people, which is something I don't do. So my opinion/review may not apply to those who are looking to play this with randomers, and I can say this is a game you don't play on your own as it's heavily geared towards a co-operative experience, and that's a good thing.Gameplay: Overall, the experience was very enjoyable. There is a lot of 'immersion' going on coupled with the excellent quality of sounds that make things intense. We found it most enjoyable with the Escape mode which, in my opinion, is the games main selling point and I think the developer should strongly consider developing this mode further as it does need to be fleshed out with more maps. Right now there is only a limited few actual Escape maps available and I'm not entirely sure how much the game randomises the rounds/maps but I'd imagine not by a lot.The game is very well paced and you find yourself never wanting to go back to the horde mechanics of L4D with it's fast zombies. The zombies here are much slower, but in a strange sense, much more deadlier. Your ammo is limited and getting attacked by zombies can result in an infection. It also adds greater tension to gameplay when your backed up in a corner, limited ammo and trying to fend off an encroaching horde. I do feel the game needs some balancing in terms of the infection mechanic during co-op. Because infected players can keep on coming at you, and at you, and your ammo supply is very limited in this game. It does change the pace a lot when that happens, forcing the players to hurry, but some sort of balancing might be needed there. Perhaps a longer respawn time for infected players?Map Design: The maps, despite the small amount of Escape ones, are very well done. The ones we did, Biotech and the Police Department one, are very large. Our game session in the PD one was 66 minutes long. The only thing holding this game back is the lack of similar maps. I would love (even pay) for a good quality large map-pack.Sound: If there's one thing I can say I like best about Cotagion, it's the sound. The sound is very impressive and very underated in any reviews I've seen. Coupled with the excellent music and the backdrop of high quality zombie moans, you've got yourself a terrifying experience. The weapon sounds are also impressive which is surprising considering so many top studios fail at producing good quality sounds. I can't stress enough that the sound quality in this game is by far the best I've seen in most other games I've played.Graphics: I've seen one review that called the graphics in this game 'dated'... I laughed. They're not AAA graphics by any sense of the imagination, but they are not decades old either. The graphics do their job. I would say they are a cut above the average but I've not heard any complaints from my mates who've tried it out and I can't say I've got any complaints either.Overall I'd recommend this game. I've gotten this game on sale at 75% off. I think if the game had more maps, and considering its geared towards co-operative play, I'd say it would then be worth the original price. Then again the counter-arguement to that is your apparently getting all future DLC and content for free? If that's the case then the original price may not be so bad, but the developer doesn't make it clear, or at least, I can't find it, on where or what future dlc might be in the works other than what's listed on the front page."
